body: Hi @mwakaba2, Could you try the latest ORT(1.8)? the default package uses thread pool instead of OMP since 1.8.0 as it provides optimal performance for most of models.
Hi @wangyems ! Thanks for the quick reply. Sure! I can try that and report back.

Hi @wangyems I tested with the latest package and the slowdown is much less. However, onnxruntime is still slow compared to vanilla Tensorflow (2x - 14x slower). I'm comparing Google's v2.5 Enterprise tensorflow version (internally uses OMP) with onnx converted Tensorflow models (v1.8.1). Is this expected?
Model Description | intra_op_num_threads | QPS | Average Latency (p50) | P90 Latency | P95 Latency | P99 Latency -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- Vanilla tensorflow | 4 | 10.29 | 97.22 | 0.02 | 102.62 | 103.41 Vanilla tensorflow | 8 | 9.62 | 103.92 | 0.04 | 113.77 | 115.77 Vanilla tensorflow | 2 | 7.29 | 137.21 | 0.02 | 144.09 | 145.23 Onnx conversion + dynamic quantization | 2 | 5.08 | 197.03 | 0.06 | 205.95 | 207.75 Onnx conversion + dynamic quantization | 4 | 2.57 | 389.68 | 0.27 | 409.97 | 416.14 Onnx conversion | 2 | 2.27 | 440.32 | 0.13 | 457.13 | 460.24 Onnx conversion + dynamic quantization | 8 | 1.25 | 799.33 | 0.63 | 832.22 | 836.45 Onnx conversion | 4 | 1.22 | 822.81 | 0.63 | 850.66 | 861.56 Tensorflow lite + dynamic quantization | 2 | 1.01 | 989.32 | 0.06 | 1000.73 | 1003.17 Tensorflow lite + dynamic quantization | 4 | 1.01 | 990.11 | 0.05 | 999.35 | 1003.44 Tensorflow lite + dynamic quantization | 8 | 1.01 | 994.06 | 0.09 | 1007.49 | 1013.89 Onnx conversion | 8 | 0.68 | 1471.27 | 3.52 | 1552.69 | 1563.76
I also noticed with v1.8, the onnx converted pytorch models are 1.25x slower than v1.7 openmp enabled. engine | version | model_source | device | precision | optimizer | io_binding | model_name | inputs | batch_size | sequence_length | datetime | test_times | QPS | average_latency_ms | latency_variance | latency_90_percentile | latency_95_percentile | latency_99_percentile | OMP_NUM_THREADS | OMP_WAIT_POLICY | OMP_ENABLED | inter_op_num_threads | intra_op_num_threads -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- onnxruntime | 1.8.1 | pt | cpu | int8 | TRUE | TRUE | bert-base-uncased | 1 | 1 | 128 | 2021-07-15 18:11:14 | 100 | 43.56 | 22.96 | 0 | 25.26 | 25.95 | 27.64 | 8 | ACTIVE | TRUE | 1 | 8 onnxruntime | 1.7.0 | pt | cpu | int8 | TRUE | TRUE | bert-base-uncased | 1 | 1 | 128 | 2021-06-17 20:12:49 | 100 | 54.06 | 18.5 | 0 | 18.72 | 18.86 | 19.31 | 8 | ACTIVE | TRUE | 1 | 8
Thanks @mwakaba2 for the report! I'll take a closer look

Hi @mwakaba2, here are something I found:

1. I was able to reproduce the bad performance using your docker with gcr.io/deeplearning-platform-release/tf2-cpu.2-5:latest. If you take a closer look, this docker image has some environment pre-installed:
       KMP_AFFINITY=granularity=fine,verbose,compact,1,0
       KMP_BLOCKTIME=0
       KMP_INIT_AT_FORK=FALSE
       KMP_SETTINGS=1
  What you can do is to unset those variables from your container(just for onnxruntime run) by:
       unset KMP_AFFINITY
       unset KMP_BLOCKTIME
       unset KMP_INIT_AT_FORK
       unset KMP_SETTINGS
  Then you should be able to get a better-than-tensorflow performance from onnxruntime

2. It's expected that pytorch-converted onnx has a better performance than tf-converted onnx. The reason is that our transformers optimizer misses some of the fusions in tf-converted onnx graph. We will support them in ORT 1.9 release.

3. I didn't notice that there is a perf regression in ORT 1.8 compared with 1.7 in my environment.

@wangyems Thanks so much for taking the time to reproduce the results!

1. I'll try unsetting the env variables for onnxruntime and share my results. Just curious, did you see the environment variables in the deep learning image Dockerfile? If so, do you have a link to it?

2. Makes sense. Thanks for the clarification! I look forward to the ORT 1.9 release!

3. To clarify, I have OMP_NUM_THREADS set to 8 threads and using N2 instances on GCP (n2-standard-16). These instances support Intel Advanced Vector Extensions 512 (Intel AVX-512) and Intel Deep Learning boost (Intel DL Boost) which boosts int8 performance. This might not be an issue if I unset the environment variables, so I'll check the pytorch results too.

> @wangyems Thanks so much for taking the time to reproduce the results!
> 
> 1. I'll try unsetting the env variables for onnxruntime and share my results. Just curious, did you see the environment variables in the deep learning image Dockerfile? If so, do you have a link to it?
> 2. Makes sense. Thanks for the clarification! I look forward to the ORT 1.9 release!
> 3. To clarify, I have OMP_NUM_THREADS set to 8 threads and using N2 instances on GCP (n2-standard-16). These instances support Intel Advanced Vector Extensions 512 (Intel AVX-512) and Intel Deep Learning boost (Intel DL Boost) which boosts int8 performance. This might not be an issue if I unset the environment variables, so I'll check the pytorch results too.

Regarding the your question in 1, I saw those variables during the tensorflow run, didn't attempt to find deep learning image Dockerfile. Those env variables catch my attention since I was not able to reproduce the slow perf on onnx without using the docker.

@wangyems Unsetting the env variables fixed it! The onnxruntime is 2x faster than the vanilla tensorflow model. 
As for the pytorch model performance, the latest onnxruntime is still 1.17x slower than executing with the openmp package.
@mwakaba2 Cool! I'll dig a bit more with the 1.8 vs 1.7 openmp on pytorch-converted onnx. Thanks for reporting the performance. Closing this issue now, feel free to reopen if you have more questions.
